    ('POLI 4P02', 'Ancient Political Theory', 'Political theory of the ancient world, spanning texts from the Near East, Greece, Rome or China. Topics may include democracy, justice, power, tragedy, gender and ecology.', 'D3', 'M', '1300-1600', 'SEM', '', 'Instructor: Dolgert,Stefan', 'Location: MCA241'),
    ('POLI 4P03', 'Modern Political Theory', 'Modern political theory examined in selected texts. Topics may include historicism, consent, progress, equality or a selected author such as Rousseau, Kant, Hegel.', 'D2', 'W', '1300-1600', 'SEM', '', 'Instructor: Bradshaw, Leah', 'Location: PLZ311'),
    ('POLI 4P10', 'Issues in Local Government', 'Policy making and service delivery in local government including economic development, fire, parks, policing, public health, recreation and social services.', 'D3', 'T', '1400-1700', 'SEM', 'Prerequisites: Prerequisite(s): POLI 3P11 or permission of the instructor.', 'Instructor: Heritz, Joanne', 'Location: TH315'),
    ('POLI 4P16', 'Global Migration:canada in a Comparative Cont', 'Global migration patterns, immigrant and refugee admission and integration policies, the trafficking of persons and smuggling, and the relation between migration and development.', 'D2', 'W', '900 -1200', 'SYN', 'Prerequisites: Prerequisite(s): POLI 2P12 (2F12) or permission of the instructor.', 'Instructor: Tossutti, Livianna', 'Location: SYNC'),
    ('POLI 4P17', 'Canadian Politics in the Digital Age', 'Impact of digital technology and innovation on political institutions in Canada. Implications of these changes for democracy.', 'D2', 'M', '1300-1600', 'SYN', 'Prerequisites: Prerequisite(s): POLI 2P12 (2F12) or permission of the instructor.', 'Instructor: Goodman, Nicole', 'Location: SYNC'),
    ('POLI 4P19', 'The Canadian Judicial Process', 'The structure, functions, and political dimension of the judiciary in Canada. Topics may include judicial decision-making, appointment and independence; the policy impact of judicial rulings; the criminal process; the influence of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms on the judicial system; and the players in the judicial process, including judges, interest groups and governments.', 'D2', 'F', '1000-1300', 'SYN', 'Notes: Open only to majors. See course description for re strictions list. Must hold a minimum of 14.0 credits with a major a verage of 70% or approval to Year IV (honours). POLI 2P12 (2F12) strongly recommended. This course may be offered in multiple modes of delivery. The method of delivery will be listed on the academic timetable, in the applicable term.', 'Instructor: Hennigar, Matthew A', 'Location: SYNC'),
    ('POLI 4P21', 'The Global Digital Political Economy', 'Intersection between economics and politics, emphasizing understanding how issues such as data governance, intellectual property and internet governance are shaping global economic governance, trade and development.', 'D2', 'T', '900 -1200', 'SYN', 'Notes: Open only to majors. See course description for re strictions list. Must hold a minimum of 14.0 credits with a major a verage of 70% or approval to Year IV (honours). this course may be offered in multiple modes of delivery. The method of delivery will be listed on the academic timetable, in the applicable term.', 'Instructor: Haggart,Blayne', 'Location: SYNC'),
    ('POLI 4P22', 'Canada & the Developing World', 'Canadas policies and practices in addressing global inequalities in wealth and power. Topics may include Canadas international assistance policies directed to lower and middle-income countries, ethical considerations, and international cooperation to address the differential impacts of global developments.', 'D3', 'W', '1300-1600', 'SEM', 'Notes: Open only to majors. See course description for re strictions list. Must hold a minimum of 14.0 credits with a major a verage of 70% or approval to Year IV (honours). this course may be offered in multiple modes of delivery. The method of delivery will be listed on the academic timetable, in the applicable term.', 'Instructor: Dashwood,Hevina', 'Location: GLB110 — (GLN-B 110)'),
    ('POLI 4P34', 'Comparative Judicial Systems', 'Global expansion of judicial power and the role of courts in democratization, rights protection, political centralization, and resolving societal conflict. Domestic as well as supranational courts from around the world are considered, representing both common law and civil law systems. Topics include the success and failure of the rights revolutions, the judicialization of politics, court reform, and justifications for judicial review.', 'D3', 'M', '900 -1200', 'SEM', 'Notes: Open only to majors. See course description for re strictions list. Must hold a minimum of 14.0 credits with a major a verage of 70% or approval to Year IV (honours). POLI 2P31 and POLI 2P32 (2F30) strongly recommended. This course may be offered in multiple modes of delivery. The method of delivery will be listed on the academic timetable, in the applicable term.', 'Instructor: Hennigar, Matthew A', 'Location: MCD304'),
    ('POLI 4P36', 'Comp Dem in Global Age:reform, Rev & Reversal', 'Analysis of the origins, processes, and outcomes of democratization and de-democratization in countries around the world.', 'D2', 'T', '1300-1600', 'BLD', 'Notes: Open only to majors. See course description for re strictions list. Must hold a minimum of 14.0 credits with a major a verage of 70% or approval to Year IV (honours). Blended - This course will primarily run in-person . There may be some classes held on-line. POLI 2P31 and POLI 2P32 (2F30) strongly recommended. This course may be offered in multiple modes of delivery. The method of delivery will be listed on the academic timetable, in the applicable term.', 'Instructor: Lupien, Pascal', 'Location: GSB308'),
    ('POLI 4P38', 'Nationalism & Ethnic Politics', 'Theory and case studies of the origins and resolution of national conflict, the mobilization of ethnic groups and the role of international forces in what have been viewed traditionally as domestic conflicts. Case studies situate Canadas ethnic tensions within a broader comparative perspective.', 'D3', 'W', '900 -1200', 'SEM', 'Notes: Open only to majors. See course description for re strictions list. Must hold a minimum of 14.0 credits with a major a verage of 70% or approval to Year IV (honours). POLI 2P31 and POLI 2P32 (2F30) strongly recommended. This course may be offered in multiple modes of delivery. The method of delivery will be listed on the academic timetable, in the applicable term.', 'Instructor: Hamilton, Paul', 'Location: MCD304'),
    ('POLI 4P41', 'Labour Law & the Charter of Rights & Freedoms', 'Application of Charter rights and freedoms, notably expression and association, to labour law in Canada.', 'D3', 'F', '900 -1200', 'SEM', 'Prerequisites: Prerequisite(s): one of, one POLI credit numbered 1(alpha)90 to 1(alpha)99, one LABR credit numbered 1(alpha)90 to 1(alpha)99, CANA 1F91.', 'Instructor: Braley-Rattai, Alison', 'Location: MCD304'),
    ('POLI 4P50', 'Machinery of Government', 'Structures and processes of federal and provincial government in Canada. Emphasis on the operation of government departments, central agencies, regulatory agencies and crown corporations.', 'D2', 'T', '1300-1600', 'SEM', 'Prerequisites: Prerequisite(s): POLI 2P99 (2Q98) or permission of the instructor.', 'Instructor: Heritz, Joanne', 'Location: MCC304'),
    ('POLI 4P54', 'Business-Government Relations', 'Politics and management of relations between business organizations and governments in Canada emphasizing current research and issues. Topics include theories of business-government relations, the legislative and regulatory environment of business, public enterprise and privatization, lobbying, and interaction among government, business, media and labour.', 'D3', 'T', '900 -1200', 'SEM', 'Crosslisting: also offered as LABR 4P54', 'Instructor: Heritz, Joanne', 'Location: MCD303'),
    ('POLI 4P68', 'Social Movements & Globalization', 'Restructuring of social movements from around the world in new alliances for global justice. Topics may include relations between local and global scales, cross-cultural collaborations, tensions between unity and diversity, conflicts and unequal power relations in networks and North-South inequalities. May include indigenous movements, transnational feminism, the anti-corporate globalizations movement and environmentalism.', 'D2', 'T', '1300-1600', 'SEM', '', 'Instructor: Conway, Janet', 'Location: STH456'),
